                                "stop": 9.985,
                                "byte_start": 89740,
                                "byte_stop": 129760,
                                "text": "Justice Breyer has the opinion this morning in 05-1629, Gonzales versus Duenas-Alvarez."
                            }
                        ]
                    },
                    {
                        "start": 9.985,
                        "stop": 268.043,
                        "byte_start": 129760,
                        "byte_stop": 0,
                        "speaker": {
                            "ID": 15139,
                            "name": "Stephen G. Breyer",
                            "href": "https:\/\/api.oyez.org\/people\/stephen_g_breyer",
                            "last_name": "Breyer",
                            "roles": [
                                {
                                    "id": 2785,
                                    "type": "scotus_justice",
                                    "date_start": 775890000,
                                    "date_end": 0,
                                    "appointing_president": "Bill Clinton",
                                    "role_title": "Associate Justice of the Supreme Court of the United States",
                                    "institution_name": "Supreme Court of the United States",
                                    "href": "https:\/\/api.oyez.org\/preson_role\/scotus_justice\/2785"
                                }
                            ],
                            "thumbnail": {
                                "id": 32682,
                                "mime": "image\/png",
                                "size": 49908,
                                "href": "https:\/\/api.oyez.org\/sites\/default\/files\/stephen_g_breyer_0.png"
                            },
                            "length_of_service": 7777,
                            "identifier": "stephen_g_breyer"
                        },
                        "text_blocks": [
                            {
                                "start": 9.985,
                                "stop": 24.529,
                                "byte_start": 129760,
                                "byte_stop": 187960,
                                "text": "The Immigration Law provides for the removal from the United States of an alien who has been convicted of \u201ca theft offense\u201d for which the term of imprisonment is at least one year."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 24.529,
                                "stop": 38.393,
                                "byte_start": 187960,
                                "byte_stop": 243340,
                                "text": "Now the question presented here is whether the term \u201ctheft offense\u201d which of here is not immigration statute includes aiding and abetting of theft offense."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 38.393,
                                "stop": 42.976,
                                "byte_start": 243340,
                                "byte_stop": 261730,
                                "text": "The Ninth Circuit thought it didn\u2019t but we hold it does."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 42.976,
                                "stop": 54.523,
                                "byte_start": 261730,
                                "byte_stop": 307915,
                                "text": "What the Immigration Act does is it list offences and conviction for any one of those offences can subject an alien to removal from the United States."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 54.523,
                                "stop": 62.849,
                                "byte_start": 307915,
                                "byte_stop": 341142,
                                "text": "Now, our problem of course is that the states have a lot of different definitions of crimes like burglary or theft."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 62.849,
                                "stop": 74.099,
                                "byte_start": 341142,
                                "byte_stop": 386178,
                                "text": "So how do you know if a particular state definition falls within the crime theft offence or burglary, or some other listed crime."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 74.099,
                                "stop": 105.287,
                                "byte_start": 386178,
                                "byte_stop": 510938,
                                "text": "This court has applied an approach which was set forth Taylor v. United States and Shepherd v. United States and that approach says in this to solve of this problem what you do is you look for the generic definition of an offense like burglary, which is the most common state definition, and if the state statute would list the crime that falls within that common definition then it fits and it\u0027s a theft offense or a burglary or whatever."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 105.287,
                                "stop": 128.46,
                                "byte_start": 510938,
                                "byte_stop": 603621,
                                "text": "So we apply that framework to a person who is convicted of violating a particular section of the California Vehicle Code that doesn\u2019t say theft but it criminalizes the taking of a vehicle without the owners consent or the aiding in abetting of a taking of a vehicle without the owners consent."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 128.46,
                                "stop": 132.016,
                                "byte_start": 603621,
                                "byte_stop": 617831,
                                "text": "So the question is what about an aider and abettor."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 132.016,
                                "stop": 142.45,
                                "byte_start": 617831,
                                "byte_stop": 659627,
                                "text": "Does he like a principal fall within the scope of generic definition of theft as most states apply that term."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 142.45,
                                "stop": 148.893,
                                "byte_start": 659627,
                                "byte_stop": 685332,
                                "text": "Well we end up thinking that it does, it does fall within it because we looked up."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 148.893,
                                "stop": 165.227,
                                "byte_start": 685332,
                                "byte_stop": 750742,
                                "text": "However, jurisdiction considers the matter and every jurisdiction as far as we can tell has \u201cexpressly abrogated the distinction\u201d between principals on the one hand and aiders and abettors who would help a principal before or during the crime."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 165.227,
                                "stop": 192.442,
                                "byte_start": 750742,
                                "byte_stop": 859516,
                                "text": "Now since every state has oblige that distinction then the term theft is now used in the criminal codes of most states does cover aiders and abettors as well as principals and therefore the aiders and abettors have to fall within the term \u201ctheft\u201d as it\u0027s used generically in the federal statute and that\u2019s why we reverse the Ninth Circuit."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 192.442,
                                "stop": 216.684,
                                "byte_start": 859516,
                                "byte_stop": 956483,
                                "text": "In addition, the Duenas-Alvarez argues, well, California\u2019s law is special and not the same as other states in a particular respect, namely they have the special doctrine called the natural and probable consequences doctrine which could hold the person liable for natural and probable consequences even though he never intended to do the thing."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 216.684,
                                "stop": 230.771,
                                "byte_start": 956483,
                                "byte_stop": 1012907,
                                "text": "Or we looked that up and the cases that we read convinced us that California doesn\u2019t have a special doctrine in that respect that it\u0027s closing up to the doctrine of the other states to be treated similarly."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 230.771,
                                "stop": 244.027,
                                "byte_start": 1012907,
                                "byte_stop": 1065884,
                                "text": "Then Duenas-Alvarez makes two more arguments and he says \u201cwell this statute penalizes joyriding and it also penalizes an aider and abettor who is an accessory after the fact."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 244.027,
                                "stop": 253.193,
                                "byte_start": 1065884,
                                "byte_stop": 1102560,
                                "text": "Now there we say that was not in the question presented that Ninth Circuit didn\u2019t decided, and so the Ninth Circuit didn\u2019t look at that on remand."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 253.193,
                                "stop": 262.506,
                                "byte_start": 1102560,
                                "byte_stop": 1139862,
                                "text": "The result is we have reversed the Ninth Circuit on the question they have decided and we are sending it back for further work on these other questions."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 262.506,
                                "stop": 268.043,
                                "byte_start": 1139862,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "Justice Stevens has filed an opinion concurring in part and dissenting in part."
                            }
                        ]
                    }
